facts.value:
William Bocock was born 29 February 1796 in Market Rasen, Lincolnshire, described by Charles Dickens as the sleepiest town in England. He was christened 9 March 1796 at the parish church, Market Rasen St. Thomas the Apostle. Just nine days after the baptism of her first child, Mary Maltby, wife of John Bocock, died and was buried in the St. Thomas churchyard. Four years later on 10 July 1800, John Bocock married Mary Dove and six more children were born to them.
When John Bocock, Williams father, died in 1818 at the comparatively early age of 45, William most likely was able to support himself. He was married for the first time 12 June 1820 at Scawby St. Hybald, Lincolnshire, to Hannah Dixon, daughter of John Dixon, who had been identified as the toll collector at Peckfield Bar, Ledsham, Yorkshire, when she was christened in 1792. Peckfield was once a notable spot on the Great North Road from London to York.
This match seems to have provided William with the inspiration for an occupation as well as a wife. Or perhaps the occupation led him to his wife? For the rest of his life, William moved from toll bar to toll bar on the British turnpike system, supplementing his earnings as a toll collector with shoemaking. Roads in England had historically been the responsibility of each local parish, although this worked a hardship on the people who lived in sparsely populated areas with rough terrain. Many roads in Britain were not publicly financed, however, but built or maintained by private turnpike trusts individually authorized by an Act of Parliament. In 1825, in the early years of William Bococks career, about 1,000 trusts controlled 18,000 miles of road in England and Wales, but even then the turnpike system comprised only about a fifth of British roads, with the rest maintained by parishes. 
A turnpike trust would usually be responsible for about 20 miles of roadway and would collect tolls from long-distance coach travelers, freight wagons, and livestock drovers.  Not all who used the turnpike had to pay a toll. For example, according to a local history of the Brentford High Street, pedestrians, the royal family, soldiers on the march, post horses carrying mail, church goers on Sunday, funeral processions, carriages on election days, carts carrying road mending materials, agricultural implements or manure and horses going to water all passed through the gates free. A toll collector, or pikeman, either bid for running a toll gate or was hired to do so. The toll collector and his family typically lived in small cottages provided by the trust. These toll cottages often had front bays where the toll collector could observe the road and the traffic. William Bocock had become a pikeman at the peak of the turnpike system.
William and Hannah Dixon Bococks first child, Joseph Bocock, was christened 18 February 1821 and died later that same year. Because Josephs christening was also recorded in non-conformist records, this event provides evidence of the familys religious affiliation. Although William Bocock observed the requirements of the established church (along with everyone else before the advent of civil registration), the familys religious associations were among the non-conformists, most likely Wesleyan Methodist. 
William and Hannahs next child, Mary Ann Bocock, was born later the same year, and her 13 December 1821 christening record also appeared in non-conformist records, as did the 25 March 1824 christening of her younger brother, Thomas Bocock. Up to this point, the young family has been living in Market Rasen. 
With the birth of their daughter, Jane Bocock, 30 December 1824, the family was recorded as living at Newstead Toll Bar, Lincolnshire, on the eastern approach to Stamford in the southwestern corner of Lincolnshire. Although they worshipped at Barn Hill Wesleyan Methodist Chapel in Stamford, when Jane died at 18 months, she was buried at Uffington just east of Stamford where her burial is recorded in the parish register. (Non-conformists had few burying grounds and were dependent on the established church for burials.) John Bocock, their last son, was born 1 January 1826, also at Newstead Toll Bar. Later that year, Hannah Dixon Bocock died at Scawby, where she had been married and where she had family to care for her. She was buried in the St. Hybalds churchyard 26 November 1826. William was left a widower at 32 with three surviving children, the oldest barely five years old.
One year later on 15 November 1827, William remarried at Balderton, Nottinghamshire. His new wife, Hannah Winks, had been born in 1800 at Cowbit, Lincolnshire, a daughter of William Winks and Mary White. Their first child, a son, William Winks Bocock, was born 27 February 1829 at the Balderton Gate Toll House. His mother did not long survive his birth, dying 17 April 1829 in Balderton, leaving William a widower once more but now with four small children to support and care for, including the new baby.
William must have looked within his Methodist community for a wife. He found a new companion in Sarah Brough, now 31 years old and living in nearby Nottingham. Sarah, born 5 April 1799 in Mansfield, Nottinghamshire, the daughter of James Brough and Jane Bowskill, had been orphaned at the age of six, with little known about her life between her mothers death and her marriage. William and Sarah were married at Nottingham St. Mary the Virgin 26 April 1830, both signing their names to the marriage register.
Their first daughter, our Hannah, undoubtedly named for Williams deceased wives, was born 22 February 1831 at the Balderton Gate Toll House, located on the approach to Newark-on-Trent on the Great North Road between London and Edinburgh. The Toll-Bar House no longer stands at No. 261, London Road (but two photos of it can be seen on flickr.com). Sarah Bocock, their second daughter and mostly likely named for her mother, was born 24 June 1832, also at Balderton. However, when Sarah was two years old, she contracted smallpox and was left blind. 
Almost five years later, the family was living at Tinsley Toll Bar, east of Sheffield, when Elizabeth Bocock was born 11 May 1837, a few weeks before the beginning of civil registration in England and Wales. The Tinsley Toll House was situated on Sheffield Road, at the junction with Dead Mans Hole Lane (which led to a ford), in an area sometimes called Templeborough, close to the boundary of the Tinsley and Rotherham parishes. The Toll House stood on the right-hand side of the tree- and hedge-lined road and on the Sheffield side of the gates. It was a square, whitewashed, two-story cottage with the typical bay window. The whitewashed weigh house was on the south side of Sheffield Road. 
When their next child, Samuel Bocock, was born 27 January 1841, William was listed as a shoemaker on his sons birth certificate and residing at Oakwell in Barnsley. But six months later, when the first 1841 U.K. census was taken, William, now 45, was listed as toll collector at the Oak Well Bar. Sarah had responsibility now only for William Winks (12), Hannah (10), Sarah (8), Elizabeth (4), and Samuel (listed as Sl), who was four months old. 
Mary Anne, Williams oldest daughter by his first marriage, had gone into service and she was found in Caistor, Lincolnshire in the same 1841 census. She would later marry Robert Procter Smith and they would live in Gainsborough with their children. The older sons were on their own and doing well. At a house warming many years later 30 December 1908, Elizabeth told her assembled family that their Grandfather Bocock was known for his honesty and integrity and that his employer valued him so highly that he persuaded my three brothers to leave their places of employment and take high positions of trust in his service. They, through their good salaries dependability and good habits became independently rich.  The brothers indeed all prospered as agents for a glass manufacturer. Thomas married Sarah Cundell and John married her sister Ann Cundell, daughters of Robert and Mary Cundell of Rotherham. William Winks Bocock never married and died intestate. The distribution of his estate relieved the poverty of his younger sisters families, for which they were very grateful.
When Emma Bocock, the youngest of William Bococks children, was born 27 June 1843, he was the toll collector at Broadfield Bar on the southwestern approach to Sheffield, the Nether Edge. The city of Sheffield is situated in a shallow bowl with roads radiating in all directions. The toll road through Broadfield Bar ran from Sheffield to Owler Bar with the name of the toll bar taken from the nearby Broadfield plantation or estate. The Toll House where the family lived was located on Abbeydale Road nearly opposite the junction with Belper Avenue. The house was built about 1812, used until 1875, and demolished a decade later. (The City of Sheffield has several copyrighted images of the Broadfield Toll Bar cottage in its online collection at picturesheffield.com.)
While Emma was still a toddler, Samuel died 11 March 1845 of hydrocephalus. Samuel had been affectionately called the Prophet Samuel because he loved to preach, but when he died, his name appears on the certificate as William. Was it a mistake, or did his father want one last remembrance? That he loved to stand on a chair and preach suggests that the family spent enough time at chapel so that he had someone to imitate. The family was back at the Oak Well Toll House in Barnsley, but William was listed as a shoemaker on the death certificate. The Oakwell area was more industrial than Abbeydale Road. Although still rural, it was surrounded by glassworks, coal mines, their outbuildings and equipment. Samuel was buried at Barnsley St. Mary the Virgin church field.
(Continued in Stories)

facts.value:
James Brough was christened 29 March 1772 at St. Lawrence North Wingfield, Derbyshire,1 the son of William and Ann Ashley Brough, and the second of their ten children. When he was a young man, he sought work in Mansfield, Nottinghamshire, a bustling market town and center of industry about twenty miles distant. He became a framework knitter or stockinger, operating a mechanical knitting machine, also known as a stocking frame.2 On 10 January 1794, at the age of 21, he married Jane Bowskill, the almost 18-year-old daughter, the second of that name, of William Bowskill and Sarah Wann or Palfreyman, at St. Peter Mansfield.3 James signed his name to the parish register; Jane made her mark.4

Their first child William was christened 6 January 1795 in the parish church of St. Edmund Mansfield-Woodhouse,5 a mile or so from Mansfield. This record provides James Broughs occupation as F.W.K. or framework knitter.6

Their second child, a daughter named Ann, was christened at St. Peter Mansfield, 17 February 1797.7 Two more daughters followed: Sarah Brough, born 5 April 1799 and christened 9 April 1799,8 and Mary Brough, born 6 April 1801 and christened 8 April 1801.9

Framework knitting was a cottage industry.10 The men in the family typically did the knitting, the women spun the yarn and finished the hose, and children wound the hanks of wool onto cones. A master known as a hosier either leased machines to stockingers to work at home on a piecework basis or else installed several machines in a shop and employed workers to make stockings on the premises. If James Brough leased a stocking frame, perhaps Jane did the stitching and finishing, and the Brough children wound the wool on the cones. Or perhaps James worked in a larger shop in Mansfield.

While a skilled occupation might be thought to provide a good living for a family, this was not the case. The Luddite Rebellion of 1811-1817 was little more than a decade away at the time this family lived in Mansfield. Poverty-stricken framework knitters rose up against the machine owners and smashed the stocking frames in nighttime raids, not because they hated modernity, but because the prosperity had not been shared and the workers could not provide for their families.11

James and Jane Bowskill Brough returned to North Wingfield from Mansfield, possibly because of poor health, but probably because James had not succeeded in obtaining a settlement in Mansfield due to his poverty. Place of settlement was originally place of birth, children, both legitimate and illegitimate, taking their settlement from the place where they were born, and a married woman taking her settlement from that of her husband. A person could obtain a settlement elsewhere, for example, if a rent of a yearly value of 10 were paid in that place. Otherwise, according to the Poor Relief Act of 1662, a person was entitled to assistance only in the parish where he or she had legal settlement.12

In North Wingfield, James and Jane Brough would bury their daughter Ann on 28 December 1802.13 Elizabeth, their fourth daughter, would be born there and christened 22 July 1803 in St. Lawrence North Wingfield,14 the same church where her father had been christened. James himself was finally buried 7 August 1804 in the churchyard.15 He was 32 years of age at death. As poor as a stockinger, he left a widow, a nine-year-old son, and three surviving daughters, ages six, four, and two.

What became of Jane and the four surviving children after James died? According to Williams 1825 settlement examination in the Mansfield Parish Chest records,16 he had been put to work for a local farmer when his father died. Because Jane had acquired her husbands North Wingfield settlement upon their marriage, she likely didnt have to return to the parish of her birth for poor relief, but she probably needed her familys help with the little children. She may have been in ill health herself. She died the next year and was buried 22 August 1805 in Mansfield, Nottinghamshire.17 She was only 28 years old.

facts.value:
Emma Bocock was born 23 June 1843, Ecclesall-Bierlow, York, England, United Kingdom at the Broadfield Toll Bar on Abbeydale Road, where her father, William Bocock, was the tollgate keeper. She was the youngest child and fourth daughter of William Bocock and Sarah Brough. After the death of their parents, the girls continued to run the toll bridge and this is where they met Charles Law, who was preaching the gospel of Jesus Christ of Latter Day Saints.  They all accepted the truthfulness of his message, and she, along with her older sisters Hannah and Elizabeth, joined the Church and embarked in 1857 on the ship "George Washington" to immigrate to the Salt Lake Valley. It docked in Boston, Massachusetts where they stayed for about 4 months in order to earn enough money to continue their journey. She was only 13 when she left for the USA, and a few years later married Charles Law, by whom she had one surviving son, Francis Joseph. When they first arrived in Utah, they lived in their wagons and tents while working on their new home.  All 3 sisters had married Charles and worked together to build their home.  They knew what hard times were and Emma gave birth to her first baby in a chicken coop.  It was thoroughly cleaned and made comfortable and for convenience, Emma took it for her maternity room.
Emma was talented at hat making and dress making.  It was called being a milliner at that time.
After Charles' death, she married Alma Moroni Blanchard, by whom she had four surviving children, Medora Blanchard [Hickenlooper], Alma Moroni Blanchard, Jr., Sarah Elizabeth Blanchard [Ferrin], and Byron Blanchard. She died from complications of childbirth 21 March 1873, Springville, Utah, Utah Territory.
